00:52:00.250 --> 00:52:06.650
The Euler equation is a
condition for savings

00:52:06.650 --> 00:52:09.500
optimality over time.

00:52:09.500 --> 00:52:14.660
What it says is the marginal
utility of consumption today--

00:52:14.660 --> 00:52:17.330
how much consumption is
worth to you today--

00:52:17.330 --> 00:52:18.810
should be equal to--

00:52:21.390 --> 00:52:25.230
so something times
[? marginal ?]

00:52:25.230 --> 00:52:26.730
consumption tomorrow.

00:52:26.730 --> 00:52:28.250
What's the question
being asked?

00:52:28.250 --> 00:52:31.972
It's asking the question,
imagine I saved one more

00:52:31.972 --> 00:52:33.222
dollar today.

00:52:35.600 --> 00:52:37.470
What would it be
worth tomorrow?

00:52:37.470 --> 00:52:40.360
Well, one thing that's going
to work is [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:40.360 --> 00:52:42.720
So it's going to be
worth 1 plus r.

00:52:42.720 --> 00:52:46.930
If the interest is r, I'm going
to get 1 plus r for it.

00:52:46.930 --> 00:52:48.360
Yeah?

00:52:48.360 --> 00:52:53.590
But then, utility tomorrow isn't
worth as much as it's

00:52:53.590 --> 00:52:54.460
work today.

00:52:54.460 --> 00:52:57.270
It's like tomorrow
is in the future.

00:52:57.270 --> 00:52:59.080
I want it now.

00:52:59.080 --> 00:53:00.100
So that's delta.

00:53:00.100 --> 00:53:02.170
Delta is a number less than 1.

00:53:02.170 --> 00:53:05.470
So it says that utility tomorrow
is worth only a

00:53:05.470 --> 00:53:08.350
fraction delta of
utility today.

00:53:08.350 --> 00:53:10.160
And then the last is
[? marginal ?]

00:53:10.160 --> 00:53:12.550
consumption tomorrow.

00:53:12.550 --> 00:53:17.200
So basically, imagine that the
right-hand side of that is

00:53:17.200 --> 00:53:21.480
less than the left-hand
side, OK?

00:53:21.480 --> 00:53:22.820
Then, what should I do?

00:53:22.820 --> 00:53:25.330
Well, I should [INAUDIBLE]
says the [? module ?]

00:53:25.330 --> 00:53:28.230
utility today is higher
than what it

00:53:28.230 --> 00:53:29.480
will be worth tomorrow.

00:53:33.080 --> 00:53:36.690
Or actually, let's do it the
other way If [? module ?]

00:53:36.690 --> 00:53:44.140
utility today is less than delta
times 1 plus r times U

00:53:44.140 --> 00:53:49.410
prime [? c ?] plus 1, that means
that $1 today saved will

00:53:49.410 --> 00:53:53.700
