00:58:43.340 --> 00:58:45.750
So people who are forward
looking, and they have an

00:58:45.750 --> 00:58:49.030
investment opportunity which
paid them 80% a year, they

00:58:49.030 --> 00:58:53.140
should be pumping all their
money into the future.

00:58:53.140 --> 00:58:56.280
80% a year is a great investment
opportunity.

00:58:56.280 --> 00:58:58.980
Only people who will do it are
people who are getting rich

00:58:58.980 --> 00:59:02.610
very fast, because if you're
getting rich very fast, then

00:59:02.610 --> 00:59:06.330
you don't want consumption
in the future.

00:59:06.330 --> 00:59:16.010
So that says that if we take
assume people are rational,

00:59:16.010 --> 00:59:19.370
then the fact that people are
persistently borrowing-- and

00:59:19.370 --> 00:59:22.090
I'll show you this
in a minute.

00:59:22.090 --> 00:59:24.260
I'm not making this
example up.

00:59:24.260 --> 00:59:27.620
So I'll show you the problem
in a minute.

00:59:27.620 --> 00:59:31.450
The fact that people are
persistently borrowing at 80%

00:59:31.450 --> 00:59:39.240
a year means that they must
be getting rich very fast.

00:59:39.240 --> 00:59:43.470
But in other words, since
they're not getting rich very

00:59:43.470 --> 00:59:46.620
fast, the poor seem
to remain poor.

00:59:46.620 --> 00:59:49.210
Something is wrong with this
calculation, so we're going to

00:59:49.210 --> 00:59:51.670
try to figure out what's
wrong with it.

00:59:51.670 --> 00:59:55.410
But if I take the model
seriously, and say, this is

00:59:55.410 --> 00:59:58.620
how people save, it is clear
that this implication is that

00:59:58.620 --> 01:00:01.580
the poverty should be the
vanishing phenomenon, because

01:00:01.580 --> 01:00:05.310
basically these guys have such
a wonderful investment

01:00:05.310 --> 01:00:06.180
opportunity.

01:00:06.180 --> 01:00:12.050
You an just save at 80% a year
and get a lot richer.

01:00:12.050 --> 01:00:13.350
So that's--

01:00:13.350 --> 01:00:14.237
yeah?

01:00:14.237 --> 01:00:17.870
AUDIENCE: What's the logic to
why sigma is equal to 3?

01:00:17.870 --> 01:00:19.120
PROFESSOR: Sigma
is equal to 3?

01:00:24.060 --> 01:00:28.460
So sigma is the coefficient
of risk aversion.

01:00:28.460 --> 01:00:32.550
If you look at the utility
function, and you look at--

01:00:32.550 --> 01:00:34.310
given that utility function,
how would

01:00:34.310 --> 01:00:36.660
people react to risk?

01:00:36.660 --> 01:00:37.870
That will be measured
by sigma.

01:00:37.870 --> 01:00:39.590
So you can actually
look at how people

01:00:39.590 --> 01:00:41.500
actually react to risks.

01:00:41.500 --> 01:00:49.150
I offer you $10 for sure, or
$4 with probability 1/3 and

01:00:49.150 --> 01:00:53.610
$15 with probability 2/3, and
I see whether you want then

01:00:53.610 --> 01:00:54.550
bet are not.

01:00:54.550 --> 01:00:57.130
And from that, people back
out of risk aversion.

01:00:57.130 --> 01:00:58.740
And to do that, they get
a number like 3.

01:01:03.300 --> 01:01:06.580
So this is sort of a hint
at what's going on.

01:01:06.580 --> 01:01:13.150
And I want to show you kind of
something more worrying.

01:01:13.150 --> 01:01:18.860
So here's an experiment which is
kind of a different way of

01:01:18.860 --> 01:01:20.930
getting at the same point.

01:01:20.930 --> 01:01:22.860
I showed it to you kind
of theoretically.

01:01:22.860 --> 01:01:25.120
Now I want to show it to
you as an experiment.

01:01:25.120 --> 01:01:25.970
Here's an experiment.

01:01:25.970 --> 01:01:28.700
It's an experiment with fruit
vendors and vegetable vendors

01:01:28.700 --> 01:01:29.980
in India and the Philippines.

01:01:29.980 --> 01:01:32.780
Two separate experiments
doing identical things.

01:01:37.000 --> 01:01:39.920
So fruit vending is a very,
very simple production

01:01:39.920 --> 01:01:44.110
function, OK?

01:01:44.110 --> 01:01:47.060
Very, very simple, meaning you
buy fruits in the morning, you

01:01:47.060 --> 01:01:53.500
sell all day, you get money in
the evening, you go home.

01:01:53.500 --> 01:01:57.710
Next morning, you come back,
and you buy fruit again.

01:01:57.710 --> 01:01:59.050
You sell it.

01:01:59.050 --> 01:02:04.560
It's very predictable, very
continuous, daily production.

01:02:04.560 --> 01:02:06.920
Not very high risk, actually.

01:02:06.920 --> 01:02:10.250
It's mostly you know what you
can sell, you can see the

01:02:10.250 --> 01:02:12.770
price, et cetera.

01:02:12.770 --> 01:02:18.800
So here's a table which kind
of summarizes a bit about

01:02:18.800 --> 01:02:20.930
these people.

01:02:20.930 --> 01:02:25.880
So most of these people make one
trip a day to the market.

01:02:25.880 --> 01:02:29.300
This one's for the Indian
experiment.

01:02:29.300 --> 01:02:39.850
They buy fruits worth about
1,000 rupees in the morning.

01:02:39.850 --> 01:02:42.780
They sell it, and they get
profits of over 100 rupees.

01:02:42.780 --> 01:02:46.600
That's the 10% profits
during the day.

01:02:46.600 --> 01:02:50.200
Not bad, actually.

01:02:50.200 --> 01:02:53.770
How do they run the business?

01:02:53.770 --> 01:02:57.160
70% take a loan every day.

01:03:03.310 --> 01:03:04.310
Every month--

01:03:04.310 --> 01:03:06.860
26 days-- somebody
takes a loan.

01:03:06.860 --> 01:03:10.530
So this is to buy fruit.

01:03:10.530 --> 01:03:16.100
The interest rate on the
loan per day is 5%.

01:03:16.100 --> 01:03:18.850
Basically, the way it works is
you go to the fruit seller,

01:03:18.850 --> 01:03:22.470
and he says, you want to
buy cash or credit?

01:03:22.470 --> 01:03:25.350
Cash price is this, credit
price is that.

01:03:25.350 --> 01:03:26.600
Which one's higher?

01:03:29.382 --> 01:03:29.840
AUDIENCE: Credit.

01:03:29.840 --> 01:03:32.220
PROFESSOR: Credit price
is higher, right?

01:03:32.220 --> 01:03:34.810
Basically, you get the same
fruit, so you pay more if you

01:03:34.810 --> 01:03:38.330
buy it in credit.

01:03:38.330 --> 01:03:40.395
But the advantage of credit is
you don't have to pay for it

01:03:40.395 --> 01:03:42.040
in the morning, you paid
it in the night.

01:03:42.040 --> 01:03:44.620
You go back in the evening,
and you pay for it.

01:03:44.620 --> 01:03:45.870
5% per day.

01:03:57.150 --> 01:04:00.150
So most of these people
have been in--

01:04:00.150 --> 01:04:02.770
no, I'm missing one table.

01:04:02.770 --> 01:04:06.260
Most of these people have been
in business for nine years.

01:04:06.260 --> 01:04:07.960
They do this day after day.

01:04:07.960 --> 01:04:10.260
Nine years they've
been in business.

01:04:10.260 --> 01:04:17.450
Every day, they borrow at 5%,
meaning that they come in the

01:04:17.450 --> 01:04:21.700
morning, they take, let's say,
1,000 rupees worth of fruits,

01:04:21.700 --> 01:04:24.650
but they actually get 950 rupees
worth of fruits, and

01:04:24.650 --> 01:04:27.590
then they go sell it.

01:04:27.590 --> 01:04:31.650
They say this is 1,000 rupees,
but in fact get 950 rupees at

01:04:31.650 --> 01:04:34.070
first first, and then
go sell it.

01:04:34.070 --> 01:04:37.760
Remember that daily income
is about 100 rupees.

01:04:37.760 --> 01:04:40.410
They pay 50 rupees out
of 1,000 as interest.

01:04:40.410 --> 01:04:44.900
So if they didn't pay interest,
they're earnings

01:04:44.900 --> 01:04:47.590
every day would be 50% higher.

01:04:47.590 --> 01:04:51.570
It would go from 100
to 150, roughly.

01:04:51.570 --> 01:04:53.920
So that's a huge
interest cost.

01:04:53.920 --> 01:04:59.460
Now here's a way to think about
5% a day, what it means.

01:05:03.370 --> 01:05:05.075
Suppose I took the following
strategy.

01:05:09.930 --> 01:05:14.090
Drink one less couple
of tea every day.

01:05:14.090 --> 01:05:17.550
A cup of tea costs,
in this same

01:05:17.550 --> 01:05:19.310
currency, 2 and 1/2 rupees.

01:05:19.310 --> 01:05:24.870
So let me take one less cup
every day, and I reinvest that

01:05:24.870 --> 01:05:25.900
in the business.

01:05:25.900 --> 01:05:31.740
So what I do is I drink one less
cup of tea, so I borrow.

01:05:31.740 --> 01:05:35.620
2 and 1/2 rupees less today.

01:05:35.620 --> 01:05:38.240
That means I don't pay interest
on the 2 and 1/2

01:05:38.240 --> 01:05:40.250
rupees, so I get a little
bit extra money.

01:05:40.250 --> 01:05:41.520
I reinvest that.

01:05:41.520 --> 01:05:43.410
I do that for 30 days.

01:05:43.410 --> 01:05:51.425
Every day, I drink one less
cup of tea for 30 days.

01:05:54.520 --> 01:05:56.290
At 5% a day--

01:05:56.290 --> 01:05:57.070
you should do this
calculation.

01:05:57.070 --> 01:05:58.370
It's stunning.

01:05:58.370 --> 01:06:01.310
Compound interest really
is impressive.

01:06:01.310 --> 01:06:09.160
So once you do this for 30 days,
you would have doubled

01:06:09.160 --> 01:06:11.970
your capital.

01:06:11.970 --> 01:06:15.530
So these women could double
their capital by simply having

01:06:15.530 --> 01:06:21.560
one less cup of tea every
day for 30 days.

01:06:21.560 --> 01:06:23.455
They've been in this business
for nine years.

01:06:27.900 --> 01:06:30.850
Their earnings would be 50%
more if they did this.

01:06:34.400 --> 01:06:37.470
They could pay down their entire
1,000 rupees debt by

01:06:37.470 --> 01:06:39.120
doing that for 30
days, basically.

01:06:42.890 --> 01:06:51.090
So your 1,000 rupees are
essentially just the price of

01:06:51.090 --> 01:06:52.430
30 days worth of tea.

01:06:59.500 --> 01:07:04.010
So that's sort of stunning,
if you think about it.

01:07:04.010 --> 01:07:07.970
So this goes back to the same
point I was trying to make,

01:07:07.970 --> 01:07:10.160
which is that there's some
reason to get worried that

01:07:10.160 --> 01:07:13.030
these people are somehow--

01:07:13.030 --> 01:07:15.280
they're not managing.

01:07:15.280 --> 01:07:18.050
What they're trying to do in
this experiment is they offer

01:07:18.050 --> 01:07:19.250
two treatments.

01:07:19.250 --> 01:07:24.290
They basically think that two
possible ways in which we

01:07:24.290 --> 01:07:29.510
could-- maybe one possibility is
that these people are now--

01:07:29.510 --> 01:07:33.900
they need 1,000 rupees to
survive, 100 rupees to eat

01:07:33.900 --> 01:07:37.780
every day, so they can't save.

01:07:37.780 --> 01:07:41.130
And so they're stuck.

01:07:41.130 --> 01:07:45.410
So it's not clear why
they couldn't have

01:07:45.410 --> 01:07:46.665
one cup of tea less.

01:07:49.210 --> 01:07:55.350
So they say, well, maybe if
we just pay their debt.

01:07:55.350 --> 01:07:57.110
So let's say they owe
1,000 rupees, we'll

01:07:57.110 --> 01:08:02.010
give them 1,000 rupees.

01:08:02.010 --> 01:08:04.410
Imagine that there's some reason
they can't get out it.

01:08:04.410 --> 01:08:09.940
Do they stay out of debt if
I pay them 1,000 rupees?

01:08:09.940 --> 01:08:14.440
Second possibility is that I
teach them what compound

01:08:14.440 --> 01:08:16.359
interest is.

01:08:16.359 --> 01:08:22.080
I explain to them that if you
just did this, you could save

01:08:22.080 --> 01:08:24.470
yourself a lot of money.

01:08:24.470 --> 01:08:25.790
So there are two treatments.

01:08:25.790 --> 01:08:29.579
They're experimental, so some of
them get one, some of them

01:08:29.579 --> 01:08:33.069
get the other, some
of them get both.

01:08:33.069 --> 01:08:35.029
So do you see what the
experiment is?

01:08:35.029 --> 01:08:38.870
I either go to someone and say,
you owe the food seller

01:08:38.870 --> 01:08:40.010
1,000 rupees.

01:08:40.010 --> 01:08:41.930
Here's 1,000 rupees.

01:08:41.930 --> 01:08:42.700
You're done.

01:08:42.700 --> 01:08:45.609
Now from now on, you
start from scratch.

01:08:45.609 --> 01:08:47.920
Or I go to them, and I
say, come to a class.

01:08:47.920 --> 01:08:51.370
I'll explain to you
compound interest.

01:08:51.370 --> 01:08:53.044
Or, I offer them both.

01:08:56.420 --> 01:08:57.460
So what happens?

01:08:57.460 --> 01:09:00.029
So that's the question.

01:09:00.029 --> 01:09:05.170
So some of these people, for
some reason, they had

01:09:05.170 --> 01:09:06.180
got into this debt.

01:09:06.180 --> 01:09:08.300
Let's say they were liberated
from the debt.

01:09:08.300 --> 01:09:11.899
Some people were educated on
the arithmetic component of

01:09:11.899 --> 01:09:13.149
compound interest.

01:09:15.819 --> 01:09:19.180
So training was half a day
training, where they were

01:09:19.180 --> 01:09:23.689
explained how much they spent
on interest, all these

01:09:23.689 --> 01:09:24.420
illustrations.

01:09:24.420 --> 01:09:28.330
If you save just one cup
of tea a day, it will

01:09:28.330 --> 01:09:29.250
be enough, et cetera.

01:09:29.250 --> 01:09:30.500
So all of that.

01:09:33.279 --> 01:09:34.529
Skip.

01:09:37.460 --> 01:09:39.240
So here's the result.

01:09:48.463 --> 01:09:51.140
This one's from the--

01:09:51.140 --> 01:09:51.770
[INAUDIBLE]

01:09:51.770 --> 01:09:53.945
let's see which country
this is.

01:09:57.210 --> 01:09:59.650
Philippines.

01:09:59.650 --> 01:10:00.900
From the Philippines.

01:10:04.380 --> 01:10:06.940
Here's the basic result.

01:10:06.940 --> 01:10:12.180
[? Force ?] times payoff
says if you--

01:10:12.180 --> 01:10:15.440
ignore everything else
that says, but just

01:10:15.440 --> 01:10:17.730
look at what it says.

01:10:17.730 --> 01:10:19.180
Do you have a debt?

01:10:19.180 --> 01:10:22.500
The question is, do you have
a debt from a money

01:10:22.500 --> 01:10:26.085
lender after two weeks?

01:10:29.090 --> 01:10:33.800
That number says you are 33%
less and less likely to have a

01:10:33.800 --> 01:10:36.280
debt from a money lender
after two weeks.

01:10:36.280 --> 01:10:41.640
So two weeks after I pay your
entire 1,000 rupees down,

01:10:41.640 --> 01:10:46.980
you're back to having
a loan for 5% a day.

01:10:51.340 --> 01:10:55.660
So 33% don't have a loan,
so 67% have a

01:10:55.660 --> 01:10:58.010
loan after two weeks.

01:10:58.010 --> 01:11:01.740
After six weeks, 60%
have a loan.

01:11:01.740 --> 01:11:04.780
After 10 weeks, 80%
have a loan.

01:11:04.780 --> 01:11:08.840
So basically, after 10 weeks,
that 1,000 that they had been

01:11:08.840 --> 01:11:10.190
given just vanishes.

01:11:12.750 --> 01:11:16.620
They don't seem to be able
to stay out of debt.

01:11:19.450 --> 01:11:22.110
The same results
are true for--

01:11:22.110 --> 01:11:24.910
this is the India study.

01:11:28.810 --> 01:11:32.035
So debt payoff after--

01:11:34.910 --> 01:11:35.850
first, follow up.

01:11:35.850 --> 01:11:50.300
After three months, so this
negative 10% don't have a

01:11:50.300 --> 01:11:54.390
loan, so 90% after three months
have got back a loan.

01:11:54.390 --> 01:11:59.190
So even though these the loan
was paid down, that went away

01:11:59.190 --> 01:12:01.515
within three months.

01:12:04.300 --> 01:12:11.870
And the training, just
2% had nothing.

01:12:11.870 --> 01:12:13.450
There was no effect
of training.

01:12:13.450 --> 01:12:17.210
OK, you can see, people
were trained.

01:12:17.210 --> 01:12:20.970
If you look at the training
row, that row says nothing

01:12:20.970 --> 01:12:22.670
significant in that row.

01:12:22.670 --> 01:12:26.320
That's just saying that
force times training

01:12:26.320 --> 01:12:28.040
is the effect of--

01:12:28.040 --> 01:12:30.550
if you had had a training,
what's the

01:12:30.550 --> 01:12:33.900
probability you have loan?

01:12:33.900 --> 01:12:36.760
It's positive, meaning you're
more likely to have a loan,

01:12:36.760 --> 01:12:39.180
but it's suddenly not
significance.

01:12:39.180 --> 01:12:41.803
So it's basically no effect
on whether you

01:12:41.803 --> 01:12:44.560
have a loan or not.

01:12:44.560 --> 01:12:48.860
So the fact they would explain
compound interest seems to

01:12:48.860 --> 01:12:52.120
have no effect on whether
you get a loan or not.

01:12:52.120 --> 01:12:55.460
It's kind of stunning, actually,
these results.

01:13:04.110 --> 01:13:05.360
How are people slipping?

01:13:08.170 --> 01:13:10.160
Why are they getting
back into?

01:13:10.160 --> 01:13:17.910
So one thing that you
find is that when

01:13:17.910 --> 01:13:19.160
they get any shocks--

01:13:22.790 --> 01:13:24.750
like somebody gets sick--

01:13:29.460 --> 01:13:33.900
if your debt was paid off so
that you were given the money,

01:13:33.900 --> 01:13:38.950
you are much more likely to deal
with the shock with your

01:13:38.950 --> 01:13:41.180
own money rather than
by borrowing.

01:13:41.180 --> 01:13:43.870
So what these people are doing
is they seem to be using the

01:13:43.870 --> 01:13:46.420
money to deal with shocks.

01:13:46.420 --> 01:13:49.730
So basically, there's so much
uncertainty in these people's

01:13:49.730 --> 01:13:54.230
lives that there's always
something that comes up.

01:13:54.230 --> 01:13:58.240
And when that comes up,
you use the money to

01:13:58.240 --> 01:13:59.360
deal with the problem.

01:13:59.360 --> 01:14:02.550
And then you're back borrowing,
basically.

01:14:08.770 --> 01:14:14.910
We'll start to think about what
these results mean on

01:14:14.910 --> 01:14:15.810
Tuesday, OK?

01:14:15.810 --> 01:14:19.730
So think about them.

01:14:19.730 --> 01:14:20.770
Do the reading.

01:14:20.770 --> 01:14:22.350
We'll talk more about
it on Tuesday.